[1] WHO Uganda SitRep 44
Date: Sat 5 Nov 2022
Source: WHO Uganda [abridged, edited]
https://www.afro.who.int/sites/default/files/2022-11/Ug_EVD_SitRep%2344.pdf


Key highlights:

- Today [5 Nov 2022] marks 47 days of response to the EVD outbreak; 1st case was confirmed on 19 Sep 2022.
- No newly confirmed EVD cases, deaths, or recoveries in the past 24 hours.
- Case fatality ratio (CFR) among confirmed cases is 51/132 (39%).
- A total of 1274 contacts actively being followed up in 7 districts; follow-up rate in the past 24 hours was 92%.

Data update as of 5 Nov 2022:

Confirmed cases: new 0, total 132
Confirmed deaths: new 0, total 51
Recoveries: new 0, total 61
Contacts: districts 7; active 1274; follow-up 92
Healthcare worker infections: new 0, dead 7, cumulative 18

Actions to date:

Coordination: Daily DTF [district task force]- and IMT [incident management team]-specific meetings within all affected districts; NTF [national task force] scheduled thrice a week.

Surveillance and contact tracing: A total of 2237 previously listed contacts have finished 21 days of follow-up. Of these, 174 are within the districts of Kakumiro, Fort Portal City, Kagadi, Luweero, Nakasongola, Ntungamo, and Bunyangabu.

Active contacts for follow-up within the past 24 hours are 1274 within 7 districts. Follow-up rate for contacts is at 92%.

Total alerts validated within the past 24 hours were 126, of which 34 met the suspected case definition and 9 were evacuated.

A total of 31 alerts received from 15 category #2, #3 districts: Kampala (7), Masaka (1), Mpigi (1), Wakiso (5), Amuru (1), Bushenyi (1), Gomba (4), Gulu (1), Hoima (2), Kalangala (1), Kayunga (2), Lamwo (1), Masindi (1), Mityana (1), Mpigi (2). All tested negative for EVD (SUD).

Laboratory: Total of 81 samples processed at UVRI and Mubende mobile lab within the past 24 hours. Timely sample collection upon receipt of filled CIF [case investigation form] in Mubende, daily lab review meetings held.

--
Communicated by:
Mary Marshall
<mjm2020@googlemail.com>

[The WHO numbers look promising with no new reports of cases or deaths. But then there is an extended lockdown, a definite hardship for the population affected, and early closing of schools. Furthermore, in the report below, it appears the public health infrastructure is struggling with inadequate funding.

According to Helen Branswell, "Uganda's health ministry acknowledges only confirmed #Ebola cases, which does not tell the whole picture of this outbreak. Adding the 21 people with Ebola-like symptoms & epi links who died before testing began, the outbreak has now led to 157 cases & 74 deaths."
(https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell/status/1590022305152831488)

The numbers still don't add up exactly but are close. - Mod.LK]

